{{Refimprove|date=July 2010}}
{{spanish name|Rico|Pérez}}
'''José Rico Pérez''' (13 March 1918 in [[Daya Nueva]]  – 6 July 2010 in [[Alicante]]) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] businessman who was chairman of the Spanish football club [[Hércules CF]] from 1971  until  1985.

During Rico's tenure Hércules went through the most successful era in their history spending eight consecutive seasons in the [[Primera Liga]] between 1974 and 1982, which included a fifth placed finish during the 1974&ndash;75 season .<ref>http://www.enmemoria.com/actualidad/20100706/fallece-rico-perez-presidente-historico-del-hercules.html</ref> 

Rico was also instrumental in helping [[Alicante]] become one of the cities of the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] in Spain,<ref>http://www.theleader.info/article/23786/spain/costa-blanca/death-of-hercules-most-famous-son{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and the [[Estadio José Rico Pérez|stadium]] of the city is named as him.

