'''Samuel "Sami" David Alexander''' (13 July 1862 – 8 March 1943) was a [[Croatian people|Croatian]] [[Jew]]ish industrialist, doyen of Croatian industrialists, a philanthropist and a member of the [[Zagreb]] prominent [[Alexander family]].<ref name="žz">{{harvtxt|Snješka Knežević|2011|p=48}}</ref><ref name="žuz">{{harvtxt|Ivo Goldstein|2005|pp=174, 268, 269}}</ref><ref name="obitelj">{{harvtxt|Jasminka Domaš Nalbantić|1996|pp=38, 39, 40, 44}}</ref>

==Background and family==
Alexander, known as ''Der Gescheite'' (The Smart One), was born in Zagreb to a Jewish family.<ref>{{harvtxt|Ognjen Kraus|1998|p=134}}</ref> His father, Jonas Alexander, was a merchant who came to Zagreb from [[Güssing]], [[Austria]] and his mother Roza ([[Married and maiden names|née]] Stern) was from an old influential Jewish family from Zagreb. Alexander's father was councillor at the "Croatian commercial artisan chamber".<ref name="gs">{{harvtxt|Gavro Schwarz|1939|p=}}</ref> Alexander had a younger brother, [[Šandor Alexander|Šandor]], and two sisters, Gizela and Ilka. He attended elementary and high school in Zagreb, and a business academy in [[Vienna]]. Around 1860 his father opened a grain store in Zagreb. After his education, Alexander returned to Zagreb and started to work with his father. In 1880 he moved to Sisak where he opened another grain store for his family business. There he was introduced to his future wife, Emma ([[Married and maiden names|née]] Neumann), the daughter of [[Varaždin]] businessman Wolf Neumann. With his wife Alexander had three daughters, Vera (died as a child), Gizela and Mira, and four sons, Ivo, Božidar, Branko and Dragutin. All his children were born in Sisak.<ref name="gs"/> Alexander was active member of the Israelites of Zagreb community.<ref>{{harvtxt|Imenik|1911|p=124}}</ref> Since 1885 he was the president of the choral society "Danica". In 1915 he moved back to Zagreb with his family.<ref name="gs"/><ref name="obitelj"/> Alexander was member of the society "Narodni rad - društvo židovskih asimilanata i anticionista u Hrvatskoj" (''Peoples work - Society of Jewish assimilates and anti Zionists in Croatia'').<ref name="žuz"/>

==Business career==
[[File:Cementara Croatia.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Cement factory "Croatia" in Zagreb]]
He was known as an organizational genius.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kraus|first=Ognjen|coauthors=|title=Židovi i Zagreb - Zagreb i Židovi|pages=|publisher=Židovska opčina Zagreb|date=|url=http://www.zoz.hr/files/Zagreb%20moj%20grad.pdf|language=hr}}</ref><ref name="hz">{{harvtxt|Ivo Goldstein|2001|pp=186, 187, 188}}</ref> In 1893 Alexander bought a brewery in [[Sisak]], "Sisačka pivovara".<ref name="nqy">{{harvtxt|Ivo Banac|1988|pp=409}}</ref><ref name="hz"/> In Sisak he was elected as the representative in the city assembly<ref>{{harvtxt|Imenik|1894|p=60}}</ref> and was vice president of the savings cooperatives for Sisak and surrounding areas.<ref>{{harvtxt|Imenik|1908|p=165}}</ref><ref name="hz"/> Alexander owned the ceramic factory "Titanit", chemical factory "Danica", cement factory "Croatia", colliery "Mirna", cooking oil factory "Zagreb" (now ''"Zvijezda"'', part of ''"[[Agrokor]]"'' company) and was major shareholder of [[Zagrebačka pivovara]].<ref name="nqy"/><ref name="hz"/> Alexander co-founded the "Zagreb Stock Exchange for the goods and values" (now ''"[[Zagreb Stock Exchange]]"'')<ref name="hz"/><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|coauthors=|title=Hrvatska burza u prošlosti|pages=|publisher=[[Zagreb Stock Exchange]]|date=|url=http://zse.hr/default.aspx?id=32849)|language=hr}}</ref> and was co-founder of "Zagreb assembly" (now ''"[[Zagreb Fair]]"'').<ref name="nqy"/><ref name="hz"/> He was also the elected president of "Industrialists Union" in 1919, and board member of the "Commercial Chamber".<ref name="žz"/><ref name="nqy"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Kolar|first=Mira|coauthors=|title=Zagrebačka pivovara do 1945.|pages=|publisher=[[Matica hrvatska]]|date=|url=http://www.matica.hr/HRRevija/revija032.nsf/AllWebDocs/kolar|language=hr}}</ref><ref name="hz"/> Alexander also owned several residential buildings in Zagreb. In the "Industrialists Union" he promoted and protected Croatian industry against Hungary and its economic policy in the [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian Empire]]. Under his leadership all of Croatia and Slavonia industry was assembled under the "Industrialists Union". Alexander donated a great deal of his profits to charity.<ref>{{harvtxt|Svijet|1929|p=609}}</ref><ref name="hz"/><ref name="obitelj"/>

==Later life==
Alexander was a great philanthropist who often aided the city of Zagreb, the poor and those in need.<ref name="gs"/><ref name="hz"/> In 1941 during [[World War II]], with the [[Independent State of Croatia|NDH]] regime in power, Alexander and his wife found refuge at the sanatorium in Klaićeva street. In 1942, Alexander and his wife moved to the sanatorium of Dr. Đuro Vranešić, known for saving 80 Jews, in Zelengaj street 57.<ref name="hz"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|coauthors=|title=U nedjeljnom prvi put cijela istina: Dugo se mislilo da je bio Gestapov doušnik. Sada se otkriva da je spasio 80 Židova|pages=|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|date=2011-11-04|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/duro-vranesic--prvi-put-cijela-istina-o-hrvatskom-schindleru-/985280/|accessdate=2012-06-12|language=hr}}</ref> He died there relatively peacefully at the age of 80 in 1943. Alexander was buried at the [[Mirogoj Cemetery]]. In an attempt to save themselves from the [[Ustaše]] and [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] persecution, his family was scattered all over the world. Some of them temporarily stayed in [[Perugia]], [[Italy]]. His wife and children survived the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]].<ref name="žz"/><ref name="gs"/><ref name="hz"/> Many members of Alexander family perished during the Holocaust.<ref name="hz"/> His sister Ilka was killed at the [[Jasenovac concentration camp]] in 1942 together with her son in law [[Oton Vinski]], his niece Zora was killed in 1944 at [[Auschwitz]].<ref>{{hr icon}} B.M.; HR-DAZG-1154 Obitelj Vinski; Državni arhiv u Zagrebu; 30 Listopad 2008, Zagreb</ref><ref>{{harvtxt|Ivo Goldstein|2005|p=299}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Frank|first=Robert|coauthors=|title=Ivanović: Hrvatska nije vlasnik 44 posto Ine|pages=|publisher=limun.hr|date=2011-05-10|url=http://limun.hr/main.aspx?id=748326|accessdate=2012-07-24|quote=Uz IPOIL obitelji Ivanović, vlasništvo Ine nakon Drugog svjetskog rata postala i imovina obitelji Marić. Artura Marica, jednog od velikih vlasnika hrvatskog naftnog biznisa prije rata, već na samom njegovom početku ubio je njegov vozač, agent Gestapoa. Supruga mu je ubijena u Auschwitzu 1944. godine, a država je imovinu konfiscirala sa zadnjim ispaljenim metkom.|language=hr}}</ref><ref name="obitelj"/>

